info.description:
# Introduction

GPRO App API is a development meant to serve GPRO Applications Frontend.
This document curates a selection of endpoints from the GPRO App API to show GPRO managers how to call
these selected endpoints to optimize their data collection, providing response schemas and extensive examples.
info.title: GPRO App Public API

Retrieving All Available Tracks' Preview Data.

Retrieve Track Profile Data.
- When called with no query parameters, it'll return the profile for the next race's track. 
  - If it's the `End of the Season`, it'll return a 401 response.
- If called with track id, it'll return the corresponding profile.
  - If the track id is invalid, it'll default to next race's track profile. 
    - If it's the `End of the Season`, it'll return a 401 response.
- If called without a valid token, it'll return a 401 response.
Legacy GPRO web market files download, updated hourly. Does not require Token authentication.

Query Available Drivers. - `To get the full market, please refer to the` [GetMarketFile](#operation/GetMarketFile) `endpoint`.
- A request with no query parameters will return a 1 page, 20 drivers long response, descending order, with an OA range which upper limit is the maximum OA of the Token's account league.
- 3 Sorting fields can be used, plus filters, as optional parameters, for `GPRO Supporters` only.

Retrieve Driver Profile data.
- When called with no query parameters, it'll return the profile of the Token's account driver (if there's a driver under contract). 
  - If no driver under contract, property `driName`'s value will be `Unknown driver`.
- If called with driver id, it'll return the corresponding profile.
  - If the driver id is invalid, it'll default to token's driver or `Unknown driver`, depending on the case explained above. 
- If called without a valid token, it'll return a 401 response.

Querying Available Technical Directosr. - `To get the full market, please refer to the` [GetMarketFile](#operation/GetMarketFile) `endpoint`.
- A request with no query parameters will return a 1 page, 20 TDs long response, descending order, with an OA range which upper limit is the maximum OA of the Token's account league, or the upper limit of Pro.
- 3 Sorting fields can be used, plus filters, as optional parameters, for `GPRO Supporters` only.

Retrieving TD profile data.
- When called with no query parameters, it'll return the profile of the Token's account TD (if there's a TD under contract). 
  - If not TD under contract, property `tdName`'s value will be `Unknown technical director`.
- If called with TD id, it'll return the corresponding profile.
  - If the TD id is invalid, it'll default to token's TD or `Unknown technical director`, depending on the case. 
- If called without a valid token, it'll return a 401 response.

Retrieving Last Staff Market Transfers data.
- When called with no query parameters, it'll return the transfers of the Token's account group.
- If the Token's account is retired, it'll return Elite's last transfers.
- When called with group parameter, it returns transfers for the specified group.

Retrieving Current and Next Season Calendar.
- If the endpoint is called without query parameters, it'll return the calendar for the group of the Token's account.
- If the account is inactive, it'll return Elite's calendar.
- If called with the query parameters, it'll return the chosen's group calendar.
Retrieving Currently Signed Sponsors and Ongoing Negotiations

- If called with no query parameters, it returns Available Sponsors for Tokens's group, or Elite if account is not active.
- When called with the group parameter, it returs sponsors for the specified group. - If called with bad parameter value, defaults for no query parameters are applied.
Retrieve Sponsor's profile data.

200.description:
Sponsor Profile Response
- `NegoSignSponsorProfileResponse` has more properties, expected when the ID is from a currently signed or in negotiations sponsor.
- `SponsorProfileResponse` has a few less properties, and is the expected response for the rest of the sponsors.

401.description:
Sponsor Profile Error
- `LoggedOut` is returned when the Token is invalid.
- `SponsorProfileError` is returned when the request is made with an invalid `id` query parameter.

get.description:
Retrieve Manager's Currently Signed Sponsors. - If called with no query parameters, it returns Manager's Sponsors for Tokens's group, or Elite if account is not active.
- When called with the group parameter, it returs Manager's Sponsors for the Manager's in the specified group. - If called with bad parameter value, defaults for no query parameters are applied.
Retrieve Race Setup Options
Staff & Facilities

Retrieve Race Analysis data.
- If called without the query parameter, it'll return most recent available race analysis.
  - `Beware that managers with several seasons experience and many races as supporters take considerable time to get a response back using this option.`
- Otherwise, it returns the specified race analysis.

200.description:
Race Analysis Response
- `RaceAnalysisResponse` is returned when the specified or default races are available.
- `RaceAnalysisNAResponse` is the provided response when the requested race, or default race, is not Available. E.G.: manager is not a supporter now,
was not a supporter that race, or did not start the race.

get.description:
Retrieve Economy History
- If called with no query parameters, it defaults to the first page of the table format.
- Otherwise, it returns the corresponding response to the `show` parameter value used in the request.

200.description:
Economy History Response
- `HistoryResponse` is the response that returns when called with value `table` for the `show` param. 
- `HistoryGraphResponse` is the response that returns when called with value `graph` for the `show` param. 
- `HistoryESGraphResponse` is the response that returns when called with values `egraph` or `sgraph` for the `show` param.

get.description:
Retrieve Qualy Standings and Starting Grid
- If no `group` parameter is used in the request, it returns Token's group.
  - If token's account is not activated, it defaults to Elite
- If no `part` paramater is provided, it defaults to `SG`
- Responses are 50 managers long. If used with multiple group options, it needs to be called page by page.
Get Qualy statistics.

Retrieve Testing Standings
- If no `group` parameter is used in the request, it returns Token's group.
  - If token's account is not activated, it defaults to Elite
- Responses are 50 managers long. If used with multiple group options, it needs to be called page by page.

Retrieve Season Standings
- If the endpoint is called without query parameters, it'll return the standings for the group of the Token's account.
  - If the account is inactive, it'll return Elite's standings
- If called with the query parameters, it'll return the chosen's group standings.

Retrieve Tyres Suppliers.
- If called with no query parameters, it returns tyre suppliers for the ongoing season.
- Otherwise returns tyre suppliers for the specified season.

Race Replay data.
- If called with no parameters, it returns last race for the group of the token's manager.
  - If manager is inactive, it returns Elite's last race.

Obtain the Race summary
- If no parameters are used, it defaults to Token's group and last race.
- If `group` parameter provided is invalid, it defaults to Elite.
- For a particular race, both `season` and `race` paramaters need to be specified.

Bearer.description:
Bearer token can be obtained using the `GPRO App` only. To obtain it, open the `GPRO App` menu, go to `Miscellaneous` section => `API access`.
Details on usage can be found at that section, too.

Key:
- `all:` All Groups. - `m:` All Master Groups. - `p:` All Pro Groups. - `a:` All Amateur Groups. - `r:` All Rookie Groups.

Show.name: show
Show.description:
Specifies the type of table/graph. Defaults to `table` if not specified.
Key: - `table`: headers and rows for table display mode. - `graph`: balance graph. - `sgraph`: expeditures graph. - `egraph`: earnings graph.

Display.name: display
Display.description:
Applies when used with `graph` show option. Defaults to `allincome` if not specified.
Key - `allincome`: includes all income/expenditure concepts. - `raceonly`: shows only post race balances.

SummaryGroup.name: group
SummaryGroup.description:
Race Summary Groups - Key: - `All`: All Managers. - `Master`: All Master division managers. - `Pro`: All Pro division managers. - `Amateur`: All Amateur division managers. - `Rookie`: All Rookie division managers. - `national`: Grouped by manager's nationality. Defaults to token's one. - `team`: Grouped by a specific team's members. Defaults to token's team, or 1st in the standings if token's manager is not in a team. - `teams`: Grouped by all teams. - `friends`: Grouped by token manager's friends.

- `team` and `national` require `team` and `nat` paramater to be specified, respectively, if default option is not the desired one.

example.trackDesc:
Located within the grounds of a park, this circuit is named after Mexico’s famous racing brothers Pedro and Ricardo, whose success had much to do with attracting the F1 circus here for the first time in 1963. The race was won that year by Jim Clark in the Lotus, but there was a feeling of sadness too for Ricardo Rodriguez, who had tragically lost his life at the circuit the previous year in a non-championship event.

The circuit became notorious for its excessively bumpy surface, perhaps a result of the earthquakes that frequently hit the area. The high altitude (thin air at 7,500 feet) also caused problems for both cars and drivers. The final corner (Peralta) was banked and taken at frightening speed. Mansell passed Berger there during the 1990 race to finish 2nd behind Prost and earn Ferrari a 1-2 finish.

Following serious crowd trouble during the 1970 race, Mexico lost its place on the F1 calendar and would not return until 1986. The track was altered and uprated for its return to F1 and also boasted a new pit complex. The 1992 race, the last to be staged at the Mexico City circuit, saw Mansell dominate in his active suspension Williams which cushioned the bumps superbly. Financial problems were the biggest contributor to the circuit’s second F1 exile, and to date it has not returned.
